 $x^3-y^3=(x-y)(x^2+xy+y^2)$
### Solution: \begin{align*}
x^3-y^3
&=(x-y)(x^2+xy+y^2)\\
&=(x-y)(x^2+y^2+xy)\\
&=(1)(7+x y)
\end{align*}
So, we need the value of $xy$.
\begin{align*}
(x-y)^2&=x^2-2xy+y^2\\
1^2&=7-2xy\\
\Rightarrow\qquad xy&=3\\
\end{align*}
Now, we can substitute $xy=3$ into our initial equation.
\begin{align*}
x^3-y^3&=(1)(7+3)\\
&=\boxed{10}
\end{align*}
